The difference between these two types of trees is that the Cayley ordered
 Bell trees keep track of a unary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, whereas the binary rooted trees do not.
 The Cayley ordered Bell trees can be attached to the vertices of the permutohed
ron and the ordered binary rooted trees can be attached to the vertices
 of the associahedron.
 There is a natural way to map the permutohedron to the associahedron, and
 it correponds to forgetting the unary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 In the image below, we draw the permutohedron 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{3}$
\end_inset

 as well as associahedron 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 inside of it.
 To each vertex of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

, we can attach a 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

-leaf ordered rooted binary tree, and to each vertex of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{3}$
\end_inset

, we can attach a 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

-leaf Cayley ordered Bell tree, which we do here.
 The map from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{3}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

 can be visualized by collapsing the red edge, or in terms of trees, by
 deleting stretching nodes, or in terms of algebra, by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the identity function.
 
